'''ES-PSA''', also known as '''Espasa''', was a [[RIC-series general labor droid|RIC-920 rickshaw droid]] manufactured by [[Serv-O-Droid, Inc.]]. He operated as a [[Rickshaw/Legends|rickshaw]] driver in the spaceport of [[Mos Espa/Legends|Mos Espa]] on [[Tatooine/Legends|Tatooine]], during the time of the [[Separatist Crisis/Legends|Separatist Crisis]] and the [[Clone Wars/Legends|Clone Wars]].

==Biography==
ES-PSA was designed as a general purpose labor droid with rudimentary programming, allowing it to complete basic tasks. It ended up as one of several RIC droids employed as rickshaw drivers in Mos Espa. Propelled by a pair of disc-mounted treads, ES-PSA pulled an unlicensed rickshaw through the busy spaceport streets.

Prior to the outbreak of the Clone Wars, ES-PSA transported [[Anakin Skywalker/Legends|Anakin Skywalker]] and [[Padmé Amidala/Legends|Padmé Amidala]] from a Mos Espa docking bay to [[Watto/Legends|Watto's]] junk shop, during Skywalker's search for his [[Shmi Skywalker Lars/Legends|mother]].

==Behind the scenes==
{{Quote|George wanted a big ball for the wheel. In my rough drawing, the robot was a lot bigger in relation to the cart itself. It was a lot wider too. Doug noticed it'd be too wide, so he asked me to narrow it quite a bit.|[[Marc Gabbana]]|<ref name="RIC-920 SW.com">{{SWArchive|url=episode-ii/bts/design/f20010816/index.html|text=Designs of Ep II: RIC-920}}</ref>}}
[[File:RIC-920_Concept.jpg|thumb|right|140px|RIC-920 concept art]]
During script development for [[Star Wars: Episode II Attack of the Clones|Attack of the Clones]], George Lucas knew that Anakin and Padmé needed a form of transportation to travel across [[Mos Espa/Legends|Mos Espa]]. Originally, [[Jay Shuster]] had envisioned an [[Otoga-222 maintenance droid/Legends|Otoga-222 maintenance droid]] as the rickshaw puller.<ref name="RIC-920 SW.com" />

The RIC-920 design was finalized by Marc Gabbana. Though designed to pull the repulsorlift rickshaw, Gabbana envisioned the droid and the conveyance as two separate entities that were paired together by necessity rather than by design. In the finished film, RIC-920 was an entirely computer-generated creation.<ref name="DB-RIC-920">{{DB|droid|ric920|RIC-920}}</ref>

